# CQL Schema Must Lead Deployment

## The Rule

New CQL columns must exist in production **before** the Rust binary that reads or writes them is deployed. Schema changes are additive (Cassandra `ADD` is idempotent); code changes are not — a missing column causes `InvalidRequest` at startup and puts `blog-service` in **degraded mode**.

## Checklist When Adding a Column

- [ ] `ALTER TABLE … ADD <col> <type>;` is in `migrations/<NNN>_<description>.cql`
- [ ] `scripts/run-analytics-migrations.sh` references the new migration file
- [ ] `deploy-azure.yml` "Run CQL migrations" step will fire (it runs on every deploy to `main` that touches `src/**` or `migrations/**`)
- [ ] Do **not** merge Rust code that `INSERT`s or `SELECT`s the new column until the migration file is also committed in the same PR (so the workflow applies schema before the image is updated)

## Why degraded mode is silent

`blog-service` catches the Cosmos `InvalidRequest` at startup and logs a `WARN` but continues serving. Users see request timeouts, not an error page — making this failure mode easy to miss without log monitoring.

## Bad pattern

```
feat/my-branch
  src/analytics.rs  ← references avatar_png_2 (NEW)
  # migrations/ NOT updated → deploy succeeds → container degraded
```

## Good pattern

```
feat/my-branch
  src/analytics.rs              ← references avatar_png_2 (NEW)
  migrations/004_4images.cql   ← ADD avatar_png_2 text; (NEW)
  scripts/run-analytics-migrations.sh ← 004 step added (NEW)
  # deploy-azure.yml runs migration step BEFORE image update ✓
```
